import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import image01 from './_00361-4255153417.png';
---

<article>
  <h2>Typography Scale</h2>
  <p>
    All headings scale fluidly from mobile to desktop using <code>clamp()</code>. No breakpoints needed.
  </p>

  <h1>Heading 1 — Main Page Title</h1>
  <h2>Heading 2 — Major Section</h2>
  <h3>Heading 3 — Subsection</h3>
  <h4>Heading 4 — Minor Heading</h4>
  <h5>Heading 5 — Rarely Used</h5>
  <h6>Heading 6 — Even Rarer</h6>

  <h2>Paragraphs & Inline Elements</h2>
  <p>
    This is a <strong>paragraph</strong> demonstrating various inline text elements. You can use <em>emphasis</em>
    for subtle stress, <b>bold text</b> for attention, and <i>italic text</i> for stylistic reasons. Technical terms like
    <dfn>clamp()</dfn> are defined using dfn tags.
  </p>

  <p>
    Inline code works too: <code>const result = clamp(min, val, max)</code>. For keyboard shortcuts, use kbd:
    <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd> to copy. Variables are styled like <var>x</var> and <var>y</var>. Sample output looks
    like <samp>Error 404: Not Found</samp>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Mathematical expressions use superscript and subscript: E = mc<sup>2</sup>, H<sub>2</sub>O. Abbreviations with
    tooltips: <abbr title='HyperText Markup Language'>HTML</abbr> and
    <abbr title='Cascading Style Sheets'>CSS</abbr>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Text can be <mark>highlighted</mark>, <del>deleted</del>, <ins>inserted</ins>,
    <s>struck through</s>, or <u>underlined</u>. Citations look like
    <cite>The Design of Everyday Things</cite>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <small>This is small print, typically used for legal disclaimers and fine print.</small>
  </p>

  <address>
    Written by John Doe<br />
    Email: <a href='mailto:john@example.com'>john@example.com</a><br />
    Visit: 123 Typography Lane, Web City
  </address>

  <p>
    Current time: <time datetime='2024-11-27T14:30'>November 27, 2024 at 2:30 PM</time>
  </p>

  <h2>Links & Navigation</h2>
  <p>
    Regular links look like <a href='#'>this link</a>. They inherit color from your design system. External links to
    <a href='https://example.com' target='_blank'>example.com</a> work the same way.
  </p>

  <h2>Lists</h2>
  <h3>Unordered Lists</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>First item in the list</li>
    <li>Second item with some longer text to demonstrate how multi-line list items look</li>
    <li>
      Third item with a nested list:
      <ul>
        <li>Nested item A</li>
        <li>Nested item B with more content</li>
        <li>
          Deeply nested item:
          <ul>
            <li>Level 3 item</li>
            <li>Another level 3 item</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li>Final item in the main list</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Ordered Lists</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>First step in the process</li>
    <li>Second step with detailed instructions</li>
    <li>
      Third step with substeps:
      <ol>
        <li>Substep 3.1</li>
        <li>Substep 3.2</li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>Final step to completion</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Definition Lists</h3>
  <dl>
    <dt>Clampography</dt>
    <dd>A fluid typography system based on CSS clamp() function.</dd>

    <dt>Responsive Design</dt>
    <dd>An approach to web design that makes web pages render well on a variety of devices and window sizes.</dd>

    <dt>Fluid Typography</dt>
    <dd>Typography that scales smoothly between minimum and maximum sizes based on viewport width.</dd>
    <dd>Eliminates the need for fixed breakpoints in type scales.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h2>Blockquotes</h2>
  <blockquote>
    <p>"Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication. Good design is as little design as possible."</p>
    <cite>— Dieter Rams</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>Blockquotes can be nested to show quoted replies:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>First level quote with important information.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>Nested quote showing a reply or referenced material.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Inline Quotes</h2>
  <p>
    As the saying goes, <q>practice makes perfect</q>, but remember that
    <q>perfect practice makes perfect</q> is more accurate.
  </p>

  <h2>Code Blocks</h2>
  <p>For code examples, use pre and code tags:</p>

  <pre><code>// Install Clampography
npm install clampography

// Import in your CSS
@import "clampography";

// That's it! All elements are now styled.</code></pre>

  <p>
    Inline code like <code>npm install</code> is styled differently from blocks.
  </p>

  <h2>Tables</h2>
  <table>
    <caption>Clampography Feature Comparison</caption>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>Clampography</th>
        <th>Traditional</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Fluid Scaling</td>
        <td>✓ Built-in</td>
        <td>✗ Manual</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Breakpoints</td>
        <td>✓ Not needed</td>
        <td>✗ Required</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>File Size</td>
        <td>✓ Minimal</td>
        <td>~ Variable</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
    <tfoot>
      <tr>
        <td colspan='3'>Data accurate as of November 2024</td>
      </tr>
    </tfoot>
  </table>

  <h2>Forms & Interactive Elements</h2>
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Example Form Elements</legend>
    <p>Form elements maintain consistent typography:</p>

    <p>
      Calculation result: <output>42</output>
    </p>

    <p>
      Progress indicator: <progress value='70' max='100'>70%</progress>
    </p>

    <p>
      Meter example: <meter value='0.7' min='0' max='1'>70%</meter>
    </p>
  </fieldset>

  <h2>Details & Summary</h2>
  <details>
    <summary>Click to expand installation instructions</summary>
    <p>To install Clampography, run the following command in your terminal:</p>
    <pre><code>npm install clampography</code></pre>
    <p>Then import it in your main CSS file before your other styles.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Usage with Tailwind CSS v4</summary>
    <p>Clampography is designed specifically for Tailwind CSS v4. Simply import it in your main CSS file:</p>
    <pre><code>@import "tailwindcss";
@import "clampography";</code></pre>
  </details>

  <h2>Media Elements</h2>
  <figure>
    <Image src={image01} alt='Abstract gradient representing fluid design' class='w-full h-auto rounded-lg shadow-md' />
    <figcaption>Figure 1: Responsive images scale properly within the typography system.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Horizontal Rules</h2>
  <p>Use horizontal rules to separate major sections:</p>

  <hr />

  <p>Content continues after the divider.</p>

  <h2>Special Characters & Entities</h2>
  <p>Common symbols: © ® ™ • × ÷ ± ≠ ≈ ≤ ≥ → ← ↑ ↓</p>
  <p>Quotes: " " ' ' « » ‹ › „ ‚</p>
  <p>Dashes: - – — (hyphen, en dash, em dash)</p>
</article>
